Word: Silicon (Si) is the most common material used in photovoltaics and can exist in both monocrystalline and polycrystalline forms. In its crystalline structure, Si atoms are arranged in a diamond cubic lattice, where each silicon atom is covalently bonded to four neighboring silicon atoms, forming a tetrahedral coordination. This structure ensures high carrier mobility and enables efficient light absorption and charge transport, making Si ideal for photovoltaic applications. Bond lengths in silicon are typically 2.35 Å.

Cadmium Telluride (CdTe) crystallizes in the cubic zinc blende structure and belongs to the F-43m space group. In this structure, each Cd atom is tetrahedrally coordinated to four Te atoms, and each Te atom is similarly coordinated to four Cd atoms. The Cd-Te bond length is approximately 2.81 Å. CdTe's direct band gap of 1.5 eV makes it highly suitable for photovoltaic applications, particularly thin-film solar cells.

Copper Indium Gallium Selenide (CIGS), with the general formula CuInₓGa₍₁₋ₓ₎Se₂, adopts the chalcopyrite crystal structure and belongs to the I-42d space group. In this structure, Cu, In, Ga, and Se atoms form a tetrahedrally coordinated network. Cu atoms are bonded to four Se atoms, and In/Ga atoms are bonded to four Se atoms as well. The Cu-Se bond lengths are approximately 2.46 Å, and the In/Ga-Se bond lengths are around 2.60 Å. This highly tunable material exhibits a direct band gap (1.0–1.7 eV) depending on the In/Ga ratio, enabling high-efficiency solar cells.

Amorphous Silicon (a-Si) lacks a long-range periodic lattice structure, distinguishing it from crystalline silicon. Si atoms form a random network of covalent bonds, where each Si atom is bonded to four neighbors in a tetrahedral configuration. The absence of periodicity reduces the carrier mobility but increases optical absorption due to localized states in the bandgap. Bond lengths in a-Si average around 2.35 Å, similar to crystalline Si.

Methylammonium Lead Iodide (CH₃NH₃PbI₃) is a perovskite material that crystallizes in the tetragonal space group I4/mcm. The structure consists of PbI₆ octahedra, where each Pb atom is surrounded by six I atoms in an octahedral coordination. Methylammonium (CH₃NH₃⁺) cations occupy the voids between the octahedra, balancing the charge and stabilizing the structure. Pb-I bond lengths vary between 3.10 Å and 3.18 Å. Its direct bandgap of approximately 1.55 eV and high defect tolerance make it an excellent candidate for next-generation photovoltaics.

Cesium Lead Bromide (CsPbBr₃) is a perovskite material that crystallizes in the orthorhombic space group Pnma. The structure comprises PbBr₆ octahedra, where each Pb atom is surrounded by six Br atoms. Cs cations occupy the voids between the octahedra, ensuring charge neutrality and structural stability. The Pb-Br bond lengths range from 2.84 Å to 2.89 Å. CsPbBr₃ exhibits excellent thermal and moisture stability, with a direct bandgap of 2.3 eV, making it suitable for high-efficiency and stable photovoltaic devices.

Poly(3-hexylthiophene) (P3HT) is a semiconducting polymer with a repeating thiophene unit, forming a conjugated polymer backbone. The hexyl side chains attached to the thiophene rings enhance solubility and processability. In its crystalline state, P3HT adopts a lamellar packing structure with π–π stacking distances of approximately 3.8 Å, facilitating charge transport along the polymer chains. P3HT is widely used as an electron donor in organic photovoltaic devices.

Lead Sulfide (PbS) adopts the rock salt crystal structure and belongs to the Fm-3m space group. In this structure, each Pb atom is octahedrally coordinated to six S atoms, and each S atom is similarly coordinated to six Pb atoms. The Pb-S bond length is approximately 2.97 Å. PbS has a tunable bandgap in the near-infrared region, making it suitable for quantum dot solar cells.

Cadmium Selenide (CdSe) can crystallize in either the cubic zinc blende or hexagonal wurtzite structure, depending on the synthesis conditions. In both structures, Cd atoms are tetrahedrally coordinated to Se atoms. The Cd-Se bond length is approximately 2.63 Å. CdSe quantum dots exhibit size-dependent bandgaps, making them ideal for application in multi-junction and quantum dot-enhanced solar cells.
